@NODE "use" "How do I use it?"

   To use Countdown 2000, you'll need

     @{b}1. An Amiga.@{ub} (Any should do, KS2.04+)

     @{b}2. Some way of seeing the amigas native 15khz output.@{ub} (TV, Scandoubler etc.)
          (Sorry, I couldn't do RTG output.   D'oh!)

     @{b}3. A battery backed up clock.@{ub}(unless you want it to be wrong!)



   To install Countdown 2000 you must first decide what you're going to use it as:
             (you can use it for more then one purpous if you want;)


     @{b}1.  A Millennium Countdown program.@{ub}

        - Easy, just copy this drawer to your harddrive and run 'countdown2000'.


     @{b}2. A screensaver module.@{ub}

        - A little more tricky.   First of all copy the 'countdown2000' program to C:, then go
         to your screensavers set up (I recomend Blitzblank, it may not work on other SS')
         and use the 'Execute' or whatever module.

        Then set the Command to 'c:countdown2000', the arguments to 'screensaver' (important!)
         and the Final Command to 'echo >ram:quit2000 quit'.

         If you can't set arguments then have the command as 'c:countdown2000 screensaver'.

        It @{b}should@{ub} then work as a screensaver module.

    @{b}3. A bootpictureą.@{ub}

       - Not for the faint hearted.  Again copy 'countdown2000' to C:, then near the top of your
        startup-sequence insert 'run >nil: countdown2000 ###' and just after the loadwb line put
        'echo >ram:quit2000 quit'.

       Where ### is in the first line put the time delay (in 50ths of a second) for it to stay on
        after wb has started loading. This lets you keep the bootpic up while all the WBStartup
        programs load. (it may take you a few goes to get the delay right.)


                                    @{"Okallydokally!" LINK "main"}


               ąThe bootpicture mode does @{b}NOT@{ub} work with FastIPrefs I'm afraid. No idea why ;(
@ENDNODE


@NODE "bug" "Uh-oh"

    Countdown 2000 has been tested on:

        1. An A1200/BPPC-240 & '040-25, 32megs fast, AGA.

        2. Um, An A1200/BPPC-240 & '040-25, 32megs fast, AGA.


      I've tested it thoroughly and compared the output to other countdown programs, and it seems
       to work, but that doesn't mean it'll work on your amiga.


      If, in the ammazinly unlikely event that it works perfectly on your machine, please send
       a little email to:

        Andrewcrowe@enterprise.net


      Or if it doesn't work, send an email with details to the same address.

                                    @{"Okallydokally!" LINK "main"}

@ENDNODE

